window.docContents[24].resolve({"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/Valuations-and-valued-rings/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--Valuations-and-valued-rings":{"contents":"Let  be a commutative ring and  a linearly ordered commutative monoid with zero.\nA valuation on  with values in  is a map  satisfyingThe last condition is the ultrametric (non-archimedean) inequality. The bundled mathlib object\nValuation R Γ₀ is the monoid homomorphism  carrying this extra additivity bound.\n\nA valuative relation on a commutative ring  axiomatises the comparison  of a\nvaluation () without naming the value group. It is a binary relation\n (read \"\") that is a total preorder, is compatible with\nmultiplication and addition, and for which  always and .\nEvery valuation induces one; conversely a valuative relation is induced by a canonical valuation\ninto a quotient value monoid, so the two encode the same data up to equivalence. This is mathlib's\npreferred framework for abstract valued fields, letting results be stated once and specialised.\n\nA ring  is a valued ring (with value group ) if it is equipped with a distinguished\nvaluation  () together with a compatible topology: the\nValued class records that the topology on  is the valuation topology, in which the sets\n for  form a neighbourhood basis at .\nEquivalently the open additive subgroups  are a basis of neighbourhoods of\n, making  a topological ring.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009p-adic and Adic Spaces","header":"5.1. Valuations and valued rings","id":"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/Valuations-and-valued-rings/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--Valuations-and-valued-rings"}});